Question 2.

Use FASTQC and MultiQC to summarize the fastq files for these datasets. For which diagnostics do these data fail? Should we be concerned about the quality of these data? Why or why not?

Convert fastq files to fastqc files using

fastqc fastq/*.fq.gz --outdir=fastqc/

Do MultiQC on the samples (installed and run on local machine), obtain fastqc/multiqc_report.html file.

  1. The MultiQC output shows the results that it failes at per sequence GC content section in 4 samples. Fail here could indicate a contaminated library or some other kinds of biased subset.
  2. One sample fails Adapter content. Trimmomatic command could help to address this problem.
  3. Also it fails at Sequence Duplication Level in 5 samples, which means … High duplication levels suggest over-representation of certain sequences, which might be due to PCR amplification bias or insufficient library complexity. Family members share a significant portion of their genomes, which can lead to naturally higher sequence duplication levels due to the shared genetic material.

Question 3.

Align genome sequences from these human sequencing experiment using bwa to the chrX_5MB.fa reference.

  1. Index genome
bwa index genome/chrX_5MB.fa
  1. Align fastq files to a reference genome.
bwa mem genome/chrX_5MB.fa fastq/sample.fq.gz > bwa_mem_align/sample.sam
  1. Convert SAM to BAM
samtools view -bS bwa_mem_align/sample.sam > bam/sample.bam

Question 4.

Process the reads through samtools mpileup to generate a .vcf file.

Repeat for each sample

  1. Sort bam file
samtools sort bwa_aligned_reads/sample.bam -o bwa_aligned_reads/sample.sorted.bam
  1. Index the BAM file:
samtools index bwa_aligned_reads/sample.sorted.bam
  1. Multiple sample SNP calling:
samtools mpileup -f genome/chrX_5MB.fa bwa_aligned_reads/sample.sorted.bam > mpile_vcf/sample.vcf

Question 5.

Complete this process using gatk to generate an alternative .vcf file. How do the .vcf files compare?

GATK program is not available on Amarel and has java error incompatibility. To solve this issue I downloaded gatk tarball into my folder on Amarel cluster and load java/17.0.6 version to resolve error.

module load java/17.0.6

Then run the script using bash

#!/bin/bash

module load samtools
module load bwa
module load FastQC
module load java/17.0.6

mkdir genome
mkdir bwa_aligned_reads
mkdir vcf

# Path to the reference genome
ref_genome="genome/chrX_5MB.fa"

# Index the genome
bwa index $ref_genome

# Index reference
samtools faidx $ref_genome

# Make sequence dictionary
gatk CreateSequenceDictionary -R $ref_genome

samples=("brother_short" "mother_short" "grandmother_short" "proband_short" "proband_29" "uncle_short")

# Align read adding read groups for appropriate usage for gatk
for sample in "${samples[@]}"
do
    # Align reads with BWA MEM, specifying read group information
    bwa mem -t 4 -R "@RG\tID:${sample}\tPL:ILLUMINA\tSM:${sample}" $ref_genome "fastq/${sample}.fq.qz" > "bwa_aligned_reads/${sample}.sam"
    
    # Convert SAM to BAM
    samtools view -bS "bwa_aligned_reads/${sample}.sam" > "bwa_aligned_reads/${sample}.bam"
    
    # Sort BAM file
    samtools sort "bwa_aligned_reads/${sample}.bam" -o "bwa_aligned_reads/${sample}.sorted.bam"
    
    # Index sorted BAM file
    samtools index "bwa_aligned_reads/${sample}.sorted.bam"
    
    # Call variants using GATK HaplotypeCaller
    gatk-4.5.0.0/gatk HaplotypeCaller -R $ref_genome -I "bwa_aligned_reads/${sample}.sorted.bam" -O "vcf/${sample}.vcf"
done

Question 6.

Generate a Manhattan plot, comparing the proband sequences with the sequences from the brother and uncle. List the SNPs/regions of interest.

library(vcfR)
library(ggplot2)
library(qqman)
library(dplyr)
library(DT)
process_vcf <- function(file_path) {
  # Read VCF file
  vcf <- read.vcfR(file_path)
  
  # Extract genotype data (if needed)
  geno <- extract.gt(vcf)
  
  # Create a data frame with the necessary columns
  vcf_data <- as.data.frame(vcf@fix)
  vcf_data <- vcf_data[, c('CHROM', 'POS', 'REF', 'ALT', 'QUAL')]
  
  # Convert columns to appropriate types
  vcf_data$POS <- as.numeric(vcf_data$POS)
  vcf_data$QUAL <- as.numeric(as.character(vcf_data$QUAL))
  vcf_data$logp <- vcf_data$QUAL / 10
  
  return(vcf_data)
}

# Process the VCF files
vcf_data_proband_29 <- process_vcf("proband_short.vcf")
vcf_data_proband_short <- process_vcf("proband_29.vcf")
vcf_data_brother <- process_vcf("brother_short.vcf")
vcf_data_uncle <- process_vcf("uncle_short.vcf")
vcf_data_mother <- process_vcf("mother_short.vcf")
vcf_data_grandmother <- process_vcf("grandmother_short.vcf")

vcf_data_brother$SAMPLE <- "Brother"
vcf_data_uncle$SAMPLE <- "Uncle"

Question 7.

Are the mother and grandmother heterozygous at these positions? Please show your work. Why is this important.

I took SNP positions found above and analyze mother and grandmother sequences.

mother_grandmother <- rbind(subset(vcf_data_mother, POS %in% c(diff_snp_pos)), subset(vcf_data_grandmother, POS %in% c(diff_snp_pos)))
df <- mother_grandmother


result_3 <- df %>% group_by(POS) %>% summarise(sample_count = n_distinct(SAMPLE)) %>% filter(sample_count == 2) %>% pull(POS)

result_3 <- df %>%
  filter(POS %in% result_3) %>% arrange(POS)

datatable(subset(result_3, POS %in% c(diff_snp_pos)), options = list(pageLength=6))

Looking at the table above mother and grandmother sequences are not heterozygous. Heterozygosity is important because it can indicate genetic diversity which can be beneficial for various traits. By analyzing the heterozygosity in family members, we can infer patterns of inheritance and identify mutations.
